size:11pt">LCCI believes reforms to the London Lorry Control Scheme can achieve a sustainable and flexible means of reducing frei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ght traffic on London roads at peak hours without incurring unacceptable costs to businesses.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 102.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reconfiguration of cycling infrastructure that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> involves the permanent deprivation of kerbside access will add an unacceptable burden to businesses with shop f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ronts on cycle routes, and given the propensity of these routes to bisect commercial roads, full and permanent segregation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> hasten the decline of high streets as vibrant and viable places to do business.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 102.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LCCI believes semi-segregated cycle space that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is designed to have enough permeability for vehicles to access the kerb would reduce the perceived and actual dangers experienced by cyclists yet have the necessary flexibility to allow business vehicles to deliver as close to their final destination as po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssible.</span></li></ul><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></h1><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London Chamber of Commerce and Industry (LCCI) is the capital’s largest and most representative business organisation with over 2,500 member companies from across Greater London. LCCI membership ranges from small and medium enterp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rises through to multi-national corporates. LCCI member companies operate within a mix of sectors, across the 33 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> boroughs, genuinely reflecting the broad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> business spectrum. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LCCI believes that the growth of cycling as a means of transport is positive for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as it is a sustainable means of relieving demand on overcrowded public transport. Indeed, many of our members (and the Chamber itself) actively encourage employees to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ake up cycling, either through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subsidised access to the Barclay’s Cycle Hire Scheme or through discounted bicycle purchases through “cycle to work” schemes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LCCI recognises that to enable more people to take it up, cycling must become objectively and subjectively safer. However, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suggestion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of a total ban of HGVs at peak hours in London and permanent and full segregation of cycle lanes could have se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rious repercussions for other road users, and business vehicles in particular. The rest of our written statement engages with these arguments and suggests where cyclists and business interest may align.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Proposals to Ban </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lorries</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> from </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> streets during P</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">eak Hours</span></h1><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A ban on lorries being able to operate in central London during peak hours would be impractical, has no little, or no, international precedent and would lead to extra costs on business supply chains.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impractical</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for businesses and consumers</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGVs</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are already barred from using the majority of central </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roads between the hours of 9pm and 7am, Monday to Saturday, Saturday afternoon and all day Sunday under the London Lorry Control Scheme. Further restrictions on operating at peak hours (7am</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-10am and 4pm-9pm, for instance), extending to all HGVs</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, would leave freight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> only a 6-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">hour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> window</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with which to make all deliveries. This would lead to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">significant increase in cost to all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as the utility of freight vehicles would diminish considerably. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, a firm that has one van with one driver could make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deliveries in one day. With a ban on HGVs of any tonnage, the number of hours available to make deliveries is halv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with a fall in the potential number of deliveries per vehicle as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, meaning that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">firm will now need two vehicles, with two drivers, to deliver the same amount of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">freight</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, a ban</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on HGVs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is unfeasible for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> many businesses that have ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">me-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sensitive deliveries that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> first thing in the morning:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Grocers and supermarkets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trade in fresh produce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> delivered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a day earlier than usual</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, reducing shelf life and product quality for customers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 104pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Construction firms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> require the free flow of material to and from their sites. Delaying their access to materials will reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">productive hours </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">each day, adding to the already skyrocketing costs and length of construction times </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potentially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rendering many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">current projects – commercial and residential - unviable.</span></li></ol></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 52.87pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">265,000 freight vehicles visit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on a daily basis, delivering goods and performing essential services. A ban on HGVs would fly in the face of the growing importance of freight traffic in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as the population grows and shopping habits change. Ordering groceries or clothing over the internet may lead to fewer car journeys but as a result, freight traffic increases. A ban would inevitably hamper those retailers that offer customers early mornin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g or late evening delivery slots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> making shopping online much more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">inconvenient for working people.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">International Comparisons</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a misconception that there are “lorry bans” in other European cities that have been successful without adding costs to bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">siness. Paris and Dublin are mentioned as models for UK cities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including London, to follow, but neither scheme are comparable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">what many now propose for the capital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Paris – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HGVs up to 26 tonnes can operate at any time except the evening rush hour and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lternatively fuelled (“green”) HGVs can operate at any time. Unlike London, HGVs of any size can operate during the night without restriction. There is also a long list of exceptions to which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">none</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the restrictions apply, including construction traffic, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">car transporters, removal traffic and tankers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 108pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Dublin – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any vehicle of any size can deliver or collect in Dublin at any time but HGVs with 5 or more axels (normally around 36 tonnes) incur a €10 fee when they do. The only ban exists on HGVs with 5 or more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">axels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">transiting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the central area of Dublin, not the whole. It should be noted Dublin has a wide range of exemptions for certain types of traffic.</span></li></ul></ul></ol><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Solution</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LCCI understands that large numbers of HGVs on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roads can increase the subjective danger of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cycling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for some cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, the best way to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduce the amount of freight traffic during peak hours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is to address the anomaly that prevents freight traffic accessing the vast majority of London roads during the hours of the day when roads are least</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in demand. The majority of freight traffic, with the exemption of the time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sensitive d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eliveries, such as those listed in paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> above, would rather avoid peak hour traffic if it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able to (the Freight Transport Association estimates that ev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ery additional minute of journey time incurs an additional £1 in cost) but the London Lorry Control Scheme leaves businesses and suppliers with little choice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LCCI believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">changes to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Lorry Control Scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> could lead to a significant reduct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ion in freight traffic during rush hours.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Parking and access is easier at night, journeys are quicker and use less fuel, leading to lower pollution and better air quality. The success of supply chains during the 2012 London Olympics – when enforcement of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he London Lorry Control Scheme was relaxed - showed that with the right levels of collaboration, residents’ priorities need not be compromised. In fact, freight operators adopted quiet practice including behavioural changes outlined in Transport for London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s Code of Practice and some also invested in quieter vehicles and equipment to reduce disturbance. Businesses saved time - with some delivering the same level of goods in half the time - and money by avoiding congestion charge hours and parking/loading re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strictions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> LCCI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">believes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> reforms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Lorry Control Scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> achieve a sustainable and flexible means of reducing freight traffic on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> roads at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">peak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> hour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> without incurring unacceptable costs to business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Full and Permanent </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Segregation</span></h1><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LCCI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">believes that improving cycling infrastructure is vital to increasing the safety of cyclists. LCCI has indicated to Transport for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (TfL) and the Office of the Mayor of London that we are willing to engage with them on reforms to junctions to mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e these more cycle-friendly and increasing the amount of segregated road space available to cyclists.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, LCCI is concerned that demands to provide permanent and full segregation of road space for cyclists will deprive businesses of kerbside access. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> thin slab of concrete to separate existing cycle superhighways from normal roads would prevent local businesses from receiving deliveries straight to their shop fronts. Full and permanent segregation would force suppliers to park further away, lengthening</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> journey times and possibly requiring additional labour to move goods from the parked vehicle to the shop front by foot. All of these additional burdens involve a cost which will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be passed on from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supplier to the business.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, a pub wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l be reliant on suppliers having kerbside access to deliver heavy barrels. In the absence of kerbside access, moving those barrels over longer distances add to the overall delivery time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which increases the likelihood of incurring a parking fine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">),</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> may cont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ravene health and safety legislation, and may require additional labour to move them. All of these costs will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be passed on to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landlord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a community asset which has already come under severe financial pressure leading to four pubs closing each </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">week in London alone.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">private passenger transport firms – including black cabs and private hire – require kerbside access in order to pick up and drop off their clients. Removing kerbside access along long stretches of roads will only add to j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ourney times, which unnecessarily incurs greater costs to the client, which in turn reduces the competitiveness of the business.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the location of segregated cycle spaces along high streets, it is worth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">noting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> what impact a loss of kerbside access woul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d have on the cost of doing business on our high streets and whether that will only hasten their decline as a vibrant and diverse public space.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is possible to pr</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eserve kerbside access for businesses and provide the segregation necessary to reduce the su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bjective and objective danger of cycling in London. Rather than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">building </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raised concrete barrier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> between cycle superhighways and the rest of the road space, the introduction of cats-eyes or armadillos would clearly demarcate the segregated space for cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sts whilst maintaining a degree of permeability for businesses to gain kerbside access outside of peak usage hours.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Any solution that involves the permanent deprivation of kerbside access will add an unacceptable burden to businesses with shop fronts on cy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cle routes, and given the propensity of these routes to bisect commercial roads, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">full and permanent segregation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">asten the decline of high streets as vibrant and viable places to do business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LCCI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">believes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">semi-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">segregated cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> space</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that is designed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">enough </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">permeability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> vehicles to access the kerb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">would reduce the perceived and actual dangers experienced by cyclists yet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the necessary flexibility to allow business vehicles to deliver as close to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">their final destination as possible.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 42.45pt 10pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Above 18 tonnes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Defined by HMRC as 3.5 tonnes and above</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Although it could be said that the total cost on fuel and wages would be the same, there is also the additional cost of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">purchasing and maintain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> an extra vehicle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>